014/**
015 * A palette of predefined colors as packed RGB floats, the kind {@link ColorTools} works with, plus a way to describe
016 * colors by combinations and adjustments. The description code is probably what you would use this class for; it
017 * revolves around {@link #parseDescription(String)}, which takes a color description String and returns a packed float
018 * color. The color descriptions look like "darker rich mint sage", where the order of the words doesn't matter. They
019 * can optionally include lightness changes (light/dark), and saturation changes (rich/dull), and must include one or
020 * more color names that will be mixed together (repeats are allowed to use a color more heavily). The changes can be
021 * suffixed with "er", "est", or "most", such as "duller", "lightest", or "richmost", to progressively increase their
022 * effect on lightness or saturation.
023 * <br>
024 * The rest of this is about the same as in {@link Palette}.
025 * <br>
026 * You can access colors by their constant name, such as {@code CACTUS}, by the {@link #NAMED} map using
027 * {@code NAMED.get("cactus", 0f)}, or by index in the FloatArray called {@link #LIST}. Note that to access a float
028 * color from NAMED, you need to give a default value if the name is not found; {@code 0f} is a good default because it
029 * is used for fully-transparent black. You can access the names in a specific order with {@link #NAMES} (which is
030 * alphabetical), {@link #NAMES_BY_HUE} (which is sorted by the hue of the matching color, from red to yellow to blue
031 * (with gray around here) to purple to red again), or {@link #NAMES_BY_LIGHTNESS} (which is sorted by the intensity of
032 * the matching color, from darkest to lightest). Having a name lets you look up the matching color in {@link #NAMED}.
033 */
034public class SimplePalette {
035    /**
036     * You can look up colors by name here; the names are lower-case, and the colors are packed floats in rgba format.
037     */
038    public static final ObjectFloatMap<String> NAMED = new ObjectFloatMap<String>(50);
039    /**
040     * Stores alternative names for colors in {@link #NAMED}, like "grey" as an alias for {@link #GRAY} or "gold" as an
041     * alias for {@link #SAFFRON}. Currently, the list of aliases is as follows:
042     * <ul>
043     * <li>"grey" maps to {@link #GRAY},</li>
044     * <li>"gold" maps to {@link #SAFFRON},</li>
045     * <li>"puce" maps to {@link #MAUVE},</li>
046     * <li>"sand" maps to {@link #TAN},</li>
047     * <li>"skin" maps to {@link #PEACH},</li>
048     * <li>"coral" maps to {@link #SALMON},</li>
049     * <li>"azure" maps to {@link #SKY}, and</li>
050     * <li>"ocean" maps to {@link #TEAL}, and</li>
051     * <li>"sapphire" maps to {@link #COBALT}.</li>
052     * </ul>
053     * Note that these aliases are not duplicated in {@link #NAMES}, {@link #NAMES_BY_HUE}, or
054     * {@link #NAMES_BY_LIGHTNESS}; they are primarily there so blind attempts to name a color might still work.
055     */
056    public static final ObjectFloatMap<String> ALIASES = new ObjectFloatMap<String>(20);
057    /**
058     * Lists the packed float color values in this, in no particular order. Does not include duplicates from aliases.

669     * All names for colors in this palette, with grayscale first, then sorted by hue from red to yellow to green to

671     */

674    public static final FloatArray COLORS_BY_HUE = new FloatArray(NAMES_BY_HUE.size);
675    /**
676     * All names for colors in this palette, sorted by lightness from black to white. You can fetch the
677     * corresponding packed float color by looking up a name in {@link #NAMED}.
678     */
679    public static final Array<String> NAMES_BY_LIGHTNESS = new Array<>(NAMES);
680    static {
681        NAMES_BY_HUE.sort(new Comparator<String>() {
682            public int compare(String o1, String o2) {
683                final float c1 = NAMED.get(o1, TRANSPARENT), c2 = NAMED.get(o2, TRANSPARENT);
684                final float s1 = saturation(c1), s2 = saturation(c2);
685                // a packed float color with a sign bit of 0 (a non-negative number) is mostly transparent.
686                // this also considers 0x80000000 transparent, but it's almost at the threshold.
687                if(c1 >= 0f) return -10000;
688                else if(c2 >= 0f) return 10000;
689                else if(s1 <= 0.05f && s2 > 0.05f)
690                    return -1000;
691                else if(s1 > 0.05f && s2 <= 0.05f)
692                    return 1000;
693                else if(s1 <= 0.05f && s2 <= 0.05f)
694                    return (int)Math.signum(lightness(c1) - lightness(c2));
695                else
696                    return 2 * (int)Math.signum(hue(c1) - hue(c2))
697                            + (int)Math.signum(lightness(c1) - lightness(c2));
698            }
699        });
700        for(String name : NAMES_BY_HUE) {
701            COLORS_BY_HUE.add(NAMED.get(name, TRANSPARENT));
702        }
703        NAMES_BY_LIGHTNESS.sort(new Comparator<String>() {
704            public int compare(String o1, String o2) {
705                return Float.compare(lightness(NAMED.get(o1, TRANSPARENT)), lightness(NAMED.get(o2, TRANSPARENT)));
706            }
707        });
708    }

710    private static final FloatArray mixing = new FloatArray(4);
711
712    /**
713     * Parses a color description and returns the approximate color it describes, as a packed float color.
714     * Color descriptions consist of one or more lower-case words, separated by non-alphabetical characters (typically
715     * spaces and/or hyphens). Any word that is the name of a color in this SimplePalette will be looked up in
716     * {@link #NAMED} and tracked; if there is more than one of these color name words, the colors will be mixed using
717     * {@link FloatColors#mix(float[], int, int)}, or if there is just one color name word, then the corresponding color
718     * will be used. The special adjectives "light" and "dark" change the intensity of the described color; likewise,
719     * "rich" and "dull" change the saturation (the difference of the chromatic channels from grayscale). All of these
720     * adjectives can have "-er" or "-est" appended to make their effect twice or three times as strong. Technically,
721     * the chars appended to an adjective don't matter, only their count, so "lightaa" is the same as "lighter" and
722     * "richcat" is the same as "richest". There's an unofficial fourth level as well, used when any 4 characters are
723     * appended to an adjective (as in "darkmost"); it has four times the effect of the original adjective. If a color
724     * name or adjective is invalid, it is considered the same as adding the color {@link #TRANSPARENT}.
725     * <br>
726     * Examples of valid descriptions include "blue", "dark green", "duller red", "peach pink", "indigo purple mauve",
727     * and "lightest richer apricot-olive".
728     * @param description a color description, as a lower-case String matching the above format
729     * @return a packed float color as described
730     */
731    public static float parseDescription(final String description) {
732        float intensity = 0f, saturation = 0f;
733        final String[] terms = description.split("[^a-zA-Z]+");
734        mixing.clear();
735        for(String term : terms) {
736            if (term == null || term.isEmpty()) continue;
737            final int len = term.length();
738            switch (term.charAt(0)) {
739                case 'l':
740                    if (len > 2 && term.charAt(2) == 'g') {
741                        switch (len) {
742                            case 9:
743                                intensity += 0.085f;
744                            case 8:
745                                intensity += 0.085f;
746                            case 7:
747                                intensity += 0.085f;
748                            case 5:
749                                intensity += 0.085f;
750                                break;
751                            default:
752                                mixing.add(0f);
753                                break;
754                        }
755                    } else {
756                        mixing.add(NAMED.get(term, 0f));
757                    }
758                    break;
759                case 'r':
760                    if (len > 1 && term.charAt(1) == 'i') {
761                        switch (len) {
762                            case 8:
763                                saturation += 0.175f;
764                            case 7:
765                                saturation += 0.175f;
766                            case 6:
767                                saturation += 0.175f;
768                            case 4:
769                                saturation += 0.175f;
770                                break;
771                            default:
772                                mixing.add(0f);
773                                break;
774                        }
775                    } else {
776                        mixing.add(NAMED.get(term, 0f));
777                    }
778                    break;
779                case 'd':
780                    if (len > 1 && term.charAt(1) == 'a') {
781                        switch (len) {
782                            case 8:
783                                intensity -= 0.085f;
784                            case 7:
785                                intensity -= 0.085f;
786                            case 6:
787                                intensity -= 0.085f;
788                            case 4:
789                                intensity -= 0.085f;
790                                break;
791                            default:
792                                mixing.add(0f);
793                                break;
794                        }
795                    } else if (len > 1 && term.charAt(1) == 'u') {
796                        switch (len) {
797                            case 8:
798                                saturation -= 0.175f;
799                            case 7:
800                                saturation -= 0.175f;
801                            case 6:
802                                saturation -= 0.175f;
803                            case 4:
804                                saturation -= 0.175f;
805                                break;
806                            default:
807                                mixing.add(0f);
808                                break;
809                        }
810                    } else {
811                        mixing.add(NAMED.get(term, 0f));
812                    }
813                    break;
814                default:
815                    mixing.add(NAMED.get(term, 0f));
816                    break;
817            }
818        }
819        float result = FloatColors.mix(mixing.items, 0, mixing.size);
820        if(result == 0f) return result;
821
822        return toEditedFloat(result, 0f, saturation, intensity, 0f);
823    }

841    /**
842     * Given a color as a packed RGBA float, this finds the closest description it can to match the given color while
843     * using at most {@code mixCount} colors to mix in. You should only use small numbers for mixCount, like 1 to 3;
844     * this can take quite a while to run otherwise. This returns a String description that can be passed to
845     * {@link #parseDescription(String)}. It is likely that this will use very contrasting colors if mixCount is 2 or
846     * greater and the color to match is desaturated or brownish.
847     * @param rgb a packed RGBA float color to attempt to match
848     * @param mixCount how many color names this will use in the returned description
849     * @return a description that can be fed to {@link #parseDescription(String)} to get a similar color
850     */
851    public static String bestMatch(final float rgb, int mixCount) {
852        mixCount = Math.max(1, mixCount);
853        float oklab = com.github.tommyettinger.colorful.oklab.ColorTools.fromRGBA(rgb);
854        float bestDistance = Float.POSITIVE_INFINITY;
855        final int paletteSize = namesByHue.size, colorTries = (int)Math.pow(paletteSize, mixCount), totalTries = colorTries * 81;
856        final float targetL = com.github.tommyettinger.colorful.oklab.ColorTools.channelL(oklab), targetA = com.github.tommyettinger.colorful.oklab.ColorTools.channelA(oklab), targetB = com.github.tommyettinger.colorful.oklab.ColorTools.channelB(oklab);
857        final String[] lightAdjectives = {"darkmost ", "darkest ", "darker ", "dark ", "", "light ", "lighter ", "lightest ", "lightmost "};
858        final String[] satAdjectives = {"dullmost ", "dullest ", "duller ", "dull ", "", "rich ", "richer ", "richest ", "richmost "};
859        mixing.clear();
860        for (int i = 0; i < mixCount; i++) {
861            mixing.add(colorsByHue.get(0));
862        }
863        int bestCode = 0;
864        for (int c = 0; c < totalTries; c++) {
865            for (int i = 0, e = 1; i < mixCount; i++, e *= paletteSize) {
866                mixing.set(i, colorsByHue.get((c / e) % paletteSize));
867            }
868            int idxI = ((c / colorTries) % 9 - 4), idxS = (c / (colorTries * 9) - 4);
869
870            final float result = com.github.tommyettinger.colorful.oklab.ColorTools.fromRGBA(
871                    toEditedFloat(FloatColors.mix(mixing.items, 0, mixCount), 0f, 0.175f * idxS, 0.085f * idxI, 0f));
872
873            final float dL = com.github.tommyettinger.colorful.oklab.ColorTools.channelL(result) - targetL;
874            final float dA = com.github.tommyettinger.colorful.oklab.ColorTools.channelA(result) - targetA;
875            final float dB = com.github.tommyettinger.colorful.oklab.ColorTools.channelB(result) - targetB;
876            if(bestDistance > (bestDistance = Math.min(dL * dL + dA * dA + dB * dB, bestDistance)))
877                bestCode = c;
878        }
879
880        StringBuilder description = new StringBuilder(lightAdjectives[(bestCode / colorTries) % 9] + satAdjectives[bestCode / (colorTries * 9)]);
881        for (int i = 0, e = 1; i < mixCount; e *= paletteSize) {
882            description.append(namesByHue.get((bestCode / e) % paletteSize));
883            if(++i < mixCount)
884                description.append(' ');
885        }
886        return description.toString();
887    }
